1. Overture parser extracts only 12 fragments instead of the expected ~63. The
   heuristic in split_overture_body() (lines shorter than 15 tokens within the
   first 100 lines, stopping at the first long line) is too aggressive -- it
   stops at the first line exceeding 15 tokens rather than continuing to
   accumulate short lines. The fallback (take first 63 non-empty lines) never
   triggers because the initial branch finds at least 10 fragments. The parser
   likely needs a more nuanced strategy: perhaps allowing occasional longer
   lines within the overture, or using the known structural break (the line
   "Bronze by gold, miss Douce's head by miss Kennedy's head..." which begins
   the narrative proper) as the split point.

2. Motif matching for "bronze by gold" reports 57 occurrences, which is
   suspiciously high. The partial-match logic (lines 330-341) matches on any
   single word of the motif longer than 3 characters. Since "gold" and
   "bronze" each appear independently throughout the episode, each solo
   occurrence inflates the count. Consider requiring a higher word-overlap
   threshold for multi-word motifs, or only counting partial matches when
   multiple motif words co-occur in the same sentence.

3. Same inflation problem for "When first" (40 occurrences) and "tap" (52
   occurrences). "When" alone matches many sentences (edit distance ~6 from
   "When first"), and "tap" is a 3-letter substring that appears inside words
   like "tapped," "tapping," and even "eppripfftaph." The 3-character minimum
   length filter (line 334: `len(word) > 3`) would exclude "tap" itself, but
   "when" (4 chars) passes. The partial-match strategy should be tightened:
   either raise the minimum word length, require more than one motif word to
   match, or use a sliding-window substring approach instead of word-level
   containment.

4. The consonance computation (lines 224-236) checks whether the LAST consonant
   phoneme of adjacent words matches, but it collects ALL non-vowel phonemes
   and then compares only the final element. True coda extraction should start
   from the end of the phoneme list and collect consonants backward until
   hitting a vowel. The current approach would miss multi-consonant codas and
   could misidentify consonants that are onsets of later syllables as codas in
   polysyllabic words.

5. CMU dictionary coverage is never explicitly reported. The exercise asks
   students to note which words are missing from cmudict (often Joyce's
   onomatopoeia -- the most phonetically interesting material). Adding a
   coverage percentage and a sample of the most frequent missing words would
   strengthen Exercise 2.

6. The phonetic density plot does not annotate or mark passages that critics
   have identified as the fugal stretto. Without such annotation, readers
   cannot easily verify whether density peaks correlate with structural
   features. Consider overlaying vertical lines or shaded regions for known
   stretto passages.

7. Edit-distance trajectories per motif are not plotted. The exercise asks for
   a plot of edit distance from the canonical form over the course of the
   episode (to see whether motifs become more or less distorted). The code
   collects the data but only produces the motif-score scatter plot, not a
   distance-over-time plot.

8. The cross-episode comparison only computes average densities. The exercise
   also asks for visualization comparing Sirens to Lestrygonians and Calypso.
   A grouped bar chart or overlay plot would make the comparison more
   accessible than a text table alone.
